Application of Facial Recognition with PCA and Raspberry Pi for Access Control to Luggage Lockers

Abstract:
The human face is considered to be one of the most used metrics for identification, along with prints and irises. It provides sufficient information for identification.The usage of luggage lockers in supermarkets, ports and shopping malls is a convenience that many customers use. Usually the access to these lockers is controlled by some kind of locking mechanism, e.g. an employee that is responsible for the rent of the lockers, a key mechanism or a locking with a password. While all of these methods work to some extent, we propose a methodology for improvement. The proposed solution is based on Facial Recognition using PCA and Raspberry Pi.

SECTION I.

Introduction

The human face is considered to be one of the most used metrics for identification, along with fingerprints and irises. It provides sufficient information for identification although fingerprint scanning as a technique is more accurate. Many algorithms can be used to recognize faces. There are many application areas of face recognition such as automatic passport checks, identification using credit cards or ATMs, entrance control, etc. This research area has been very popular during the past forty years.

What is face recognition? This is the process of identifying or verifying the identity of a person using a picture of their face. The process of face recognition consists of the following main steps:

  • The first step is face detection - this is the process of locating human faces in images or video clips.

  • The second step is the process of face capturing which transforms the person’s facial features into digital properties.

  • The last step is the comparison between the query-picture and pictures in the face recognition system.

This method for person identification is successfully applied but because it uses personal, biometric data, the collected data should be used responsibly and with the consent of the user. Most people are reserved towards these types of applications but regardless, the statistical data shows that lately more and more often not only young but also elder people are prone to use such functionalities [1].

In [2] different existing systems and methods for face recognition are described and compared. A comparison of the datasets for testing and training the face recognition systems and the history of face recognition is presented in [3][4]. The use cases of face recognition can be categorized into four big groups:

  • Health care, [5][6]

  • Smart homes [7][8], smart rooms [9], and smart cities [10]

  • Security and Access Control [11][12]

  • Marketing and Retail [13],[14]

In the last few years, more mobile phones are using Facial Recognition for unlocking the device, and this method is widely accepted by users - they do not have to remember passwords or to draw strange figures on the screen. Luxurious hotels and complexes control access to different services and rooms via Facial Recognition, as well.

Another Application of Facial Recognition

The usage of luggage lockers, Fig. 1, is a convenience that customers use in shopping malls, stores, amusement parks, tourist spots, stations, airports, etc. Usually, the access to these lockers, the unlocking, and locking, imposes the need of employees who are responsible for the control, or when there are no dedicated employees, a method with coins is used. The customer has to have a coin that will act as a deposit while the locker is used.

While the method with coins was very popular in recent years, nowadays it is not very applicable. With the development of devices that provide opportunities for contactless payments many people opt to use them and do not carry any cash or coins with them. Meaning that when they need to use such a locker they have to find the nearest ATM and then a place to change their money. In this case, the customer wastes time engaging in additional steps that can be shortened or removed entirely.

There was a period where the luggage lockers in shops were free and the locking mechanism was with a key that the customers had to carry with them once they locked their luggage and return it when they released the locker. In many cases, the keys went missing soon after the installation of the lockers.

Another popular type of locker from recent years is the one where there are no keys but passcodes. They do not require any deposit or payment but the customer has to remember the passcode to lock and unlock the locker. The algorithm of this method requires the pressing of several buttons and the input of a 4-digit passcode, which will be used to lock and unlock the compound. This approach makes it difficult for older customers to use the lockers and they often give up or place their luggage in already unlocked lockers and leave it unprotected risking their luggage being stolen.

Fig. 1

Luggage Lockers

Show All

In this publication, we propose a solution that controls access to such lockers with Facial Recognition based on the PCA algorithm and Raspberry Pi microcomputer. A payment module is not in the scope of our research and is not considered. We believe that this method will be accepted by all age groups and will give a solution to the problems with the lost keys, the forgotten passcodes, etc.

This publication is organized as follows: A literature review on the usage of Raspberry Pi and Facial Recognition is presented, the PCA algorithm is described, and architecture is proposed and shown, as well as a diagram of the algorithm.

SECTION II.

Literature Review

In [15] the authors are reviewing different algorithms for Facial Recognition - Principal component analysis (PCA), Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), Independent Component Analysis (ICA), Gabor Wavelet, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and others. The advantages of the combination of PCA and k-means for Facial Recognition are shown. PCA is not difficult to implement, easy to understand, and effective enough. It is based on the concept of finding the Euclidean distance to determine the proximity degree or the similarity between two objects.

In [17] the authors are building a system that can detect and recognize faces with Raspberry Pi. Their goal is to optimize the speed using the microcomputer to send the photo over the Internet to a server that makes the recognition. They use several different criteria to compare the detection and recognition rates.

The authors in [18] are also using Raspberry Pi for Face Recognition. Every image is enhanced after applying Gaussian blurring and histogram equalization. After that, every image is transformed to a one-dimensional vector with the help of a Histogram of Oriented Gradients and finally, a SVM classifier is trained.

SECTION III.

Proposed Methodology

A. Hardware

The architecture of the proposed solution can be seen in Fig. 2. The hardware used in this method is less expensive compared to a traditional architecture used for the same purpose, Fig. 3.

In the proposed setting a controller, Raspberry Pi (RPi), is used. The specifications of Raspberry Pi, Model 3B + are:

  • Quad-Core 1.4GHz Broadcom BCM2837B0 64bit CPU

  • 1GB LPDDR2 SDRAM

  • Dual-channel 2.4GHz and 5GHz IEEE 802.11.b/g/n/ac wireless LAN, Bluetooth 4.2, BLE

  • Gigabit Ethernet over USB 2.0 with throughput limited to 300 Mbit/s (3 times faster than model B)

  • Extended 40-pin GPIO header

  • Full-size HDMI

  • 4 USB 2.0 ports

  • Full-size HDMI CSI (Camera Serial Interface) camera port for connecting a camera

  • DSI (Display Serial Interface) display port for connecting a touchscreen display

  • 4-pole stereo output and composite video port

  • Micro SD port

  • 5V/2.5A DC power input

  • Power-over-Ethernet (PoE) support (requires separate PoE HAT)

The controller RPi has 28 input/output channels, GPIO, Fig. 4. In our case, these outlets should work as outputs for the control of the electromagnetic locks, shown in Fig. 5. These outlets work with a voltage of 3.3V and the value of the resistor, Ri, should be chosen in a way that the current in the base circuit of the transistor should not exceed 3mA. In the normal state, the transistor, Qi is blocked and there is no power supply to the electromagnet of the locking mechanism. In the presence of a logic 1 of GPIOi, the transistor will be unblocked and current will flow through the electromagnet, Locki, as a result of which the latch of the locking mechanism will be retracted and the door of the locker will be unlocked.

Up to 28 lockers can be controlled with one Raspberry Pi device – one for each output. Of course, this number can be increased with additional hardware.

B. Algorithm

Principal component analysis (PCA) – proposed by Karl Pearson in 1901 is one of the most used algorithms for feature selection and dimensionality reduction. Assuming that one two-dimensional image is represented by a one-dimensional feature vector, that is concatenated vectors of pixels for every row or column in the image, a rather long one-dimensional vector is obtained. When talking about FR, the most logical thing is to compare these vectors, i.e. to compare the new image against all of the images in the database, assuming that all of the images’ vectors are stored in a database. That could be quite a long and resourceful process and the performance time will increase with the increase of the stored images, rendering it useless after some time.

As a rule, the database should store photos only of the occupied lockers. The time for the response of the system should be evaluated and taken into consideration in the case of all lockers are occupied and not just only a few. Therefore one cannot rely on the possibility that the number of occupied lockers is not large.

That is the reason to use photos of faces with high quality, respectively, large size, and an algorithm, PCA, that reduces the dimension of the feature vectors. The idea of this reduction is to preserve the important and informative parts of the photo and reduce the non-informative.

The algorithm of the proposed method, Fig. 6, is as follows – the customer sees a screen showing all of the lockers – the ones that are free and available for usage are marked in green, and the taken ones – in red. The customer chooses a number and a check to see if the locker is available is initiated. If the locker is free, the customer is then urged to face the camera and wait for several seconds to be photographed and his photo saved in the database. The process is finished when the locker is locked.

If the locker is occupied a message is displayed to the customer informing him that the locker is used and asking him if he wishes to unlock it or to select another locker. This step aims to filter the mistakenly entered lock numbers. When the customer selects the option to unlock the compound he is urged, again, to face the camera. While waiting for the locker to unlock, his face is detected, photographed, and compared to the currently stored images. If the face is recognized the lock is opened and the customer can retrieve the luggage, Fig. 7.

C. Database and storing mechanism

To archive and study the use of the lockers, as well as the speed of the facial recognition, the proposed solution uses a combination of a local database and a cloud database. The local database is used to store the information about the photos of the currently used lockers as well as some statistical data that can be synchronized once a day with the cloud database.

The table containing the information about the current occupation of the lockers consists of the following columns:

  • Number of the locker (acting as a primary key);

  • Photo vector;

  • URL to the locally-stored image in the file system;

  • Date and time of occupation;

Once the locker becomes available, the information from this table is transferred to another mirror table in the same database. The purpose of that second table is to store all of the information from the day temporarily and send it to the cloud database for synchronization and analytics, such as which lockers are preferred most, what types of lockers are used the most – big ones or smaller ones, what is the average time of usage, etc. The gathered data can be also used in emergencies and robbery investigations.

This database schema aims to reduce the number of indexes with which the images will be compared in the process of face recognition.

SECTION IV.

Conclusions

Face recognition is a very active and interesting are of scientific research in the last years. More and more devices are using biometrical data based on face characteristics. That leads to the development of different algorithms for extraction and comparison of these characteristics.

In the described system the PCA algorithm with the combination of Raspberry Pi are used in order to implement a complete solution for access control to luggage lockers. A relational database is used to store feature vectors of the photos. Having in mind the factor of the speed of facial recognition the database is divided to local database and cloud database. That way the combination of PCA with Eigenface provides a good solution to the problem of facial recognition. The proposed method is fairly simple, cheap and gives good results in different areas of application.
